    "topic_zh": "苦难与恶的问题",
    "topic_en": "The Problem of Evil and Suffering",
    "core_argument_zh": "苦难问题常被用来反对上帝存在，但实际上它预设了客观道德——而客观道德恰恰需要上帝。改革宗神学认为：（1）上帝有充分的道德理由允许苦难；（2）人的有限性使我们无法完全理解上帝的旨意；（3）上帝自己在十字架上进入了人类最深的苦难；（4）上帝应许最终消除一切苦难（启示录21:4）。\n\n普兰丁格在《上帝、自由与恶的本质》中证明了\"逻辑版恶的问题\"已被解决——上帝和恶的共存在逻辑上不矛盾，因为创造拥有自由意志的存在物本身是善，自由意志的可能被滥用是恶的来源。即使麦基也承认普兰丁格的自由意志辩护成功回应了逻辑版恶的问题。\n\n当代讨论转向\"概率版恶的问题\"。\"怀疑有神论\"指出：我们有限的认知使我们没有资格判断某种苦难是否真的\"无意义\"。正如两岁孩子无法理解打针为何是好的，我们也可能无法理解上帝允许某些苦难的理由。\n\n基督教最独特的回应是位格性的：上帝在基督里亲自进入苦难最深处。十字架表明上帝不是旁观者，而是亲自承担了罪恶的终极代价。复活应许苦难的最终结局：上帝将擦去一切眼泪。",
    "core_argument_en": "The problem of evil is often used against God's existence, but it presupposes objective morality — which requires God. Reformed theology holds: (1) God has morally sufficient reasons for permitting suffering; (2) Human finitude prevents fully grasping God's purposes; (3) God Himself entered deepest suffering on the Cross; (4) God promises to eliminate all suffering (Revelation 21:4).\n\nPlantinga in 'God, Freedom, and Evil' demonstrated the logical problem of evil is resolved — God and evil's coexistence isn't logically contradictory, since creating free beings is a good, and possible misuse of free will is evil's source. Even Mackie conceded Plantinga's Free Will Defense succeeded.\n\nContemporary discussion shifted to the evidential problem. Skeptical theism responds: our limited cognition disqualifies us from judging whether any suffering is truly 'pointless.' Just as a two-year-old cannot understand vaccination's benefit, we may not grasp God's reasons for permitting certain sufferings.\n\nChristianity's most unique response is personal: God in Christ entered suffering's deepest depths. The Cross shows God personally bore the ultimate cost of evil. The resurrection promises suffering's final resolution: God will wipe every tear.",
    "common_objections": [
      {
        "objection_zh": "一个全善全能的上帝不会允许无辜的孩子受苦。",
        "objection_en": "An all-good, all-powerful God would not allow innocent children to suffer.",
        "response_zh": "这假设了如果上帝有道德上充分的理由，我们一定能知道那些理由。但这个假设是不合理的——一个无限智慧的存在完全可能有超出我们理解的理由。就像一个两岁的孩子不理解打针为什么是好的，我们也可能无法理解上帝允许某些苦难的全部原因。更重要的是，上帝并非旁观者——祂在基督里亲自承受了苦难。",
        "response_en": "This assumes that if God has morally sufficient reasons, we must be able to identify them. But this assumption is unwarranted — an infinitely wise being may well have reasons beyond our comprehension. Just as a two-year-old cannot understand why a vaccination is good, we may not grasp God's full reasons for permitting certain suffering. Crucially, God is not a bystander — He entered suffering Himself in Christ."
      },
      {
        "objection_zh": "如果上帝有计划，那人的自由意志不就没有意义了？",
        "objection_en": "If God has a plan, doesn't that make free will meaningless?",
        "response_zh": "改革宗神学区分上帝的主权旨意和人的责任。上帝是万事的第一因（first cause），但人作为第二因（secondary causes）仍有真实的选择和责任。约瑟被哥哥们卖到埃及是邪恶的行为，但上帝用它成就了拯救的目的（创世记50:20）。上帝的主权和人的责任并非矛盾，而是圣经启示中的张力性真理。",
        "response_en": "Reformed theology distinguishes between God's sovereign will and human responsibility. God is the first cause of all things, but humans as secondary causes make real choices and bear real responsibility. Joseph's brothers selling him into Egypt was evil, yet God used it for salvation (Genesis 50:20). God's sovereignty and human responsibility are not contradictory but held in tension in biblical revelation."
      },
      {
        "objection_zh": "世上有太多无意义的苦难（gratuitous evil），不可能都有理由。",
        "objection_en": "There is too much gratuitous evil in the world; it can't all have a reason.",
        "response_zh": "要论证存在“无意义的苦难“（gratuitous evil），你需要证明上帝不可能有我们不知道的理由——但这恰恰是你无法证明的。这被称为“怀疑有神论“（skeptical theism）。此外，基督教独特地提供了苦难的终极答案：不是一个理论，而是一个位格——耶稣基督在十字架上承担了全人类的苦难和罪恶，并在复活中胜过了死亡。",
        "response_en": "To argue that gratuitous evil exists, you must show God cannot have reasons unknown to us — but this is precisely what you cannot demonstrate. This is known as 'skeptical theism.' Furthermore, Christianity uniquely provides the ultimate answer to suffering: not a theory, but a Person — Jesus Christ bore all human suffering and sin on the Cross, and conquered death in the Resurrection."
      }
