        "response_en": "This mathematical analogy misunderstands the Trinity. The Trinity is not three Gods added together but one God existing in three personal modes. A more accurate analogy is 1x1x1=1. Ultimately, no finite analogy perfectly captures the infinite God's nature. The key is understanding the distinction between essence and person: three Persons share one complete divine essence, not each possessing one-third. This does not violate logic — saying 'one essence is three essences' would be contradictory, but 'one essence exists in three Persons' is not."
