        "response_en": "Reason and empathy can help us recognize the importance of human rights but cannot provide their ontological foundation. Many rational people (like Nietzsche) reached entirely different conclusions — the strong have no obligation to protect the weak. Empathy is a psychological tendency that can be trained away (as in soldiers during war). The real question is not 'Can we feel the importance of human rights?' but 'At the level of ultimate reality, do human rights really exist?' If humans are merely complex material arrangements, claiming humans have 'inherent' rights is as groundless as claiming a rock has 'inherent' rights."
