    "id": "sec-007",
    "target_worldview": "secularism",
    "topic_zh": "科学不能回答所有问题（唯科学主义的问题）",
    "topic_en": "Science Cannot Answer All Questions (The Problem of Scientism)",
    "core_argument_zh": "科学主义（scientism）认为只有科学方法才能给我们可靠的知识，但这个立场本身就是自我拆台的——\"只有科学能给我们知识\"这个声称本身不是一个科学发现，而是一个哲学立场。它无法被实验测试或观察证实。科学主义不是科学的结论，而是一种信念。\n\n科学方法预设了许多非科学的前提：（1）自然界的一致性（归纳法假设过去的规律将来也适用——但这无法被科学证明）；（2）逻辑法则的有效性（科学推理依赖逻辑，但逻辑是先验的，不是科学发现）；（3）数学的可靠性（物理学依赖数学，但数学真理不是经验发现）；（4）人类理性的可信度（我们信任大脑的推理能力——但这个信任本身不是科学实验的结果）。\n\n著名的哲学家和科学家都承认科学的局限性。物理学家约翰·波尔金霍恩指出，科学回答\"怎样\"的问题，但不能回答\"为什么\"。化学家彼得·阿特金斯虽然是无神论者，也承认科学不能解释为什么有自然律。科学是探索自然界的强大工具，但将它绝对化为唯一的知识来源就超出了它的合法范围。\n\n基督教完全支持科学研究（历史上是基督教推动了科学的诞生），但它认识到科学是人类知识的一部分，不是全部。道德知识、美学判断、形而上学真理、历史知识——这些都是真正的知识，但都不是通过科学方法获得的。",
    "core_argument_en": "Scientism holds only scientific method yields reliable knowledge, but this position is self-defeating — 'only science gives knowledge' is not itself a scientific discovery but a philosophical stance. It can't be experimentally tested or observationally confirmed. Scientism isn't a conclusion of science but a belief.\n\nScience presupposes many non-scientific premises: (1) Nature's uniformity (induction assumes past regularities continue — unprovable by science); (2) Logical laws' validity (scientific reasoning requires logic, but logic is a priori, not a scientific discovery); (3) Mathematics' reliability (physics depends on math, but mathematical truths aren't empirical discoveries); (4) Human reason's trustworthiness (we trust our brain's reasoning — but this trust itself isn't an experimental result).\n\nProminent philosophers and scientists acknowledge science's limits. Physicist John Polkinghorne notes science answers 'how' questions but not 'why.' Chemist Peter Atkins, though an atheist, admits science can't explain why natural laws exist. Science is a powerful tool for exploring nature, but absolutizing it as the only knowledge source exceeds its legitimate scope.\n\nChristianity fully supports scientific research (historically Christianity birthed modern science) but recognizes science is part of human knowledge, not all of it. Moral knowledge, aesthetic judgment, metaphysical truth, historical knowledge — all are genuine knowledge obtained through non-scientific means.",
    "common_objections": [
      {
        "objection_zh": "科学是最成功的知识获取方法，所以应该优先。",
        "objection_en": "Science is the most successful method of gaining knowledge, so it should take priority.",
        "response_zh": "科学在其适当的领域——研究物质世界的可重复现象——确实极为成功。但成功不等于独占。科学不能回答这些合法且重要的问题：数学真理为什么是真的？逻辑法则的基础是什么？什么是美？什么是善？历史事件是否发生了？我应该如何对待我的邻居？人生的目的是什么？这些问题需要哲学、伦理学、历史学、神学等其他学科的方法。将科学的成功推广为知识的垄断，就像因为锤子在钉钉子上很成功就声称锤子是唯一的工具一样。",
        "response_en": "Science is indeed extraordinarily successful in its proper domain — studying repeatable phenomena in the material world. But success does not equal monopoly. Science cannot answer these legitimate and important questions: Why are mathematical truths true? What grounds the laws of logic? What is beauty? What is goodness? Did historical events occur? How should I treat my neighbor? What is life's purpose? These require methods from philosophy, ethics, history, theology, and other disciplines. Extending science's success into a knowledge monopoly is like claiming the hammer is the only tool because it is so successful at driving nails."
      },
      {
        "objection_zh": "宗教的知识主张从未像科学那样被证实过。",
        "objection_en": "Religious knowledge claims have never been confirmed the way science's have.",
        "response_zh": "这取决于你如何定义“证实”。如果只接受实验室可重复的实验作为证据，那么你也必须排除历史学、法学和日常推理中的大量知识。基督教的核心历史宣称——耶稣的复活——可以通过历史证据方法来评估，正如我们评估任何古代历史事件一样。此外，许多科学家本身就是基督徒（如牛顿、法拉第、普朗克、柯林斯），他们不认为自己的信仰与科学矛盾。科学的方法和基督教信仰回答的是不同层面的问题。",
        "response_en": "This depends on how you define 'confirmed.' If you accept only repeatable laboratory experiments as evidence, you must also exclude vast knowledge from history, law, and everyday reasoning. Christianity's core historical claim — Jesus' resurrection — can be evaluated through historical evidence methods, just as we assess any ancient historical event. Moreover, many scientists themselves are Christians (Newton, Faraday, Planck, Collins), who see no contradiction between their faith and science. Scientific method and Christian faith address different levels of questions."
      },
      {
        "objection_zh": "科学方法是自我纠正的，这使它比宗教更可靠。",
        "objection_en": "Science is self-correcting, making it more reliable than religion.",
        "response_zh": "科学方法的自我纠正确实是其巨大优势——在其适当领域内。但'自我纠正'预设了若干非科学的前提：自然规律的一致性（为什么自然规律在未来仍然有效？），逻辑法则的有效性（科学推理依赖逻辑，但逻辑不是科学发现），以及人类理性的可靠性（为什么信任我们大脑产生的结论？）。这些前提都无法被科学方法本身证明。此外，科学的'自我纠正'功能恰恰暗示了一个超越科学的真理标准——科学向着更准确的方向'进步'，预设了一个客观真理作为衡量标准。这与基督教的认识论完全一致：上帝创造了有序的宇宙，赋予人类理性去探索它。",
        "response_en": "Science's self-correcting nature is indeed a great strength — within its proper domain. But 'self-correction' presupposes several non-scientific premises: the uniformity of nature (why should natural laws hold in the future?), the validity of logical laws (scientific reasoning depends on logic, but logic isn't a scientific discovery), and the reliability of human reason (why trust our brains' conclusions?). None of these can be proven by science itself. Moreover, science's 'self-correcting' function implies a truth standard beyond science — science 'progresses' toward greater accuracy, presupposing objective truth as a benchmark. This is fully consistent with Christian epistemology: God created an orderly universe and endowed humans with reason to explore it."
      }
    ],
