    "id": "cults-005",
    "target_worldview": "general",
    "topic_zh": "福音的独特性：恩典 vs 行为",
    "topic_en": "The Uniqueness of the Gospel: Grace vs Works",
    "core_argument_zh": "在多元化的宗教环境中，基督教的核心信息——福音——提供了独特而完整的救赎方案。福音的核心是：人因罪与上帝隔绝，无法通过自己的努力获得拯救，但上帝在基督里主动施行拯救，通过耶稣的十字架和复活使信靠祂的人与上帝和好。\n\n这个信息与所有其他宗教和世俗方案的根本区别在于\"恩典\"原则。几乎所有其他体系（宗教的和世俗的）都以某种形式的\"业绩\"为基础——做好事、积功德、遵守律法、修炼自我、为社会做贡献。基督教独特地宣告：救恩完全是上帝白白的恩典，不是人的功劳。\"你们得救是本乎恩，也因着信；这并不是出于自己，乃是上帝所赐的\"（以弗所书2:8）。\n\n这种恩典不是廉价的。迪特里希·朋霍费尔区分了\"廉价的恩典\"和\"重价的恩典\"。福音的恩典是重价的——它的代价是上帝自己在十字架上的牺牲。但对于接受者来说，它完全是白白的——你不需要也不可能赚取它。这解决了人类宗教经验中最深层的焦虑：我是否足够好？我做的够不够多？福音的回答是：不是你的好，而是基督的好。\n\n在面对其他宗教和邪教的替代方案时，基督徒需要既有真理的确信也有爱的态度——\"用温柔敬畏的心回答各人\"（彼得前书3:15）。福音不是通过强制传播的，而是通过生命见证和真理宣讲传递的。",
    "core_argument_en": "In a pluralistic religious landscape, Christianity's core message — the Gospel — provides a unique and complete salvation plan. The Gospel's core: humans are separated from God by sin, unable to save themselves, but God in Christ actively provides salvation through Jesus' cross and resurrection, reconciling believers with God.\n\nThis message's fundamental distinction from all other religious and secular systems is the 'grace' principle. Nearly all other systems (religious and secular) are 'performance'-based — doing good, accumulating merit, keeping laws, self-cultivation, contributing to society. Christianity uniquely declares: salvation is entirely God's free grace, not human achievement. 'It is by grace you have been saved, through faith — and this is not from yourselves, it is the gift of God' (Ephesians 2:8).\n\nThis grace isn't cheap. Dietrich Bonhoeffer distinguished 'cheap grace' from 'costly grace.' Gospel grace is costly — its price was God's own sacrifice on the cross. But for recipients, it's entirely free — you don't need to and cannot earn it. This resolves humanity's deepest religious anxiety: Am I good enough? Have I done enough? The Gospel answers: it's not about your goodness but Christ's.\n\nFacing alternative offers from other religions and cults, Christians need both truthful conviction and loving attitude — 'always being prepared to give an answer with gentleness and respect' (1 Peter 3:15). The Gospel spreads not through coercion but through life witness and truth proclamation.",
    "common_objections": [
      {
        "objection_zh": "约翰福音1:1应该翻译为“道是一个神”而非“道就是上帝”。",
        "objection_en": "John 1:1 should be translated 'the Word was a god,' not 'the Word was God.'",
        "response_zh": "这是耶和华见证人新世界译本的翻译，被几乎所有希腊文学者否定。在希腊文中，theos（上帝）前面没有定冠词是因为它在句中作表语（predicate nominative），这是标准的希腊文语法规则（Colwell规则），不是表示“一个神”。如果约翰想表达“一个神”，他有完全不同的表达方式。此外，在同一卷福音书中，多马直接称耶稣为“我的主！我的上帝！”（约翰福音20:28），耶稣没有纠正他，反而称赞了他的信仰。",
        "response_en": "This is the Jehovah's Witnesses' New World Translation, rejected by virtually all Greek scholars. In Greek, theos (God) lacks the definite article because it functions as a predicate nominative — this is a standard Greek grammar rule (Colwell's Rule), not an indication of 'a god.' If John meant 'a god,' he had entirely different ways to express it. Furthermore, in the same Gospel, Thomas directly addresses Jesus as 'My Lord and my God!' (John 20:28), and Jesus does not correct him but commends his faith."
      },
      {
        "objection_zh": "耶稣说“父比我大”（约翰福音14:28），证明他不是上帝。",
        "objection_en": "Jesus said 'the Father is greater than I' (John 14:28), proving he is not God.",
        "response_zh": "这节经文需要在道成肉身的背景下理解。耶稣说这话时是在他的人性中，即将走向十字架的受辱状态。腓立比书2:6-8解释了这一点：基督虽然“本有上帝的形象”，却“取了奴仆的形象”。“大”（greater）指的是地位和角色的关系，不是本质（nature）的差异——正如一位总统在职位上“大于”普通公民，但在人性本质上完全平等。同一位耶稣也说“我与父原为一”（约翰福音10:30），这只有在本质同等的前提下才有意义。",
        "response_en": "This verse must be understood in the context of the incarnation. Jesus spoke these words in his human nature, about to enter the humiliation of the Cross. Philippians 2:6-8 explains: Christ, though 'in the form of God,' 'took the form of a servant.' 'Greater' refers to positional and functional relationship, not a difference in nature — just as a president is 'greater than' an ordinary citizen in office but fully equal in human nature. The same Jesus also said 'I and the Father are one' (John 10:30), which only makes sense given essential equality."
      },
      {
        "objection_zh": "旧约没有预言弥赛亚是上帝。",
        "objection_en": "The Old Testament does not prophesy that the Messiah would be God.",
        "response_zh": "旧约有多处指向弥赛亚神性的经文。以赛亚书9:6称将来的婴孩为“全能的上帝、永在的父”。弥迦书5:2说弥赛亚的“根源从亘古、从太初就有”。但以理书7:13-14描述“人子”接受万族的敬拜——在旧约中只有上帝配受敬拜。诗篇45:6直接对弥赛亚王说“上帝啊，你的宝座是永永远远的”（希伯来书1:8引用此节指向基督）。玛拉基书3:1预言“主”（耶和华）要来到他的殿中——新约将此应用于耶稣。",
        "response_en": "The OT contains multiple passages pointing to the Messiah's deity. Isaiah 9:6 calls the coming child 'Mighty God, Everlasting Father.' Micah 5:2 says the Messiah's 'origins are from of old, from ancient times.' Daniel 7:13-14 describes the 'Son of Man' receiving worship from all nations — in the OT, only God is worthy of worship. Psalm 45:6 directly addresses the messianic king as 'God' ('Your throne, O God, is forever' — Hebrews 1:8 applies this to Christ). Malachi 3:1 prophesies 'the Lord' (Yahweh) coming to His temple — the NT applies this to Jesus."
