        "response_en": "The church did not create the canon but recognized it. God's Word carries inherent authority — the church's role was to discern which books possessed apostolic authority, just as a court discerns law rather than creating it. Canonical criteria were not decided by church vote but based on apostolicity (authored by apostles or apostolic companions), orthodoxy (consistent with confirmed apostolic teaching), and catholicity (universally used and accepted by churches). Moreover, if church authority supersedes Scripture, then when the church's teaching deviates from Scripture (as with medieval indulgences), there is no higher standard to correct the church — precisely what the Reformation opposed."
