        "response_en": "This criticism is often based on misunderstanding or oversimplification of Christian doctrine. The alleged 'contradictions' are usually surface tensions, not logical inconsistencies. The Trinity does not say that one God is simultaneously three Gods (which would indeed be a contradiction), but that one God exists in three Persons—a proposition that is completely logically consistent. The tension between predestination and human responsibility is likewise not a logical contradiction but a mystery that finite reason cannot fully comprehend about the infinite God. It is important to distinguish between logical contradiction (A and not-A both being true) and mystery (truths that transcend complete human understanding). Christianity acknowledges the existence of the latter while firmly rejecting the former. Van Til emphasized that theological mysteries are not irrational but supra-rational—they do not violate logic but transcend the full grasp of human reason. This epistemological humility is itself an expression of the Christian worldview's consistency."
