        "response_zh": "基础主义和一致性理论都面临严重的认识论问题。基础主义声称存在自明的基础信念，但什么叫「自明」？如何确定某些信念真的是自明的而不是我们的偏见？笛卡尔的「我思故我在」看似自明，但它预设了逻辑定律(如同一律)和语言意义的稳定性，这些本身都不是自明的。现代认识论早已放弃了寻找不可怀疑的基础信念的计划。一致性理论的问题在于可能存在多个彼此一致但互相矛盾的信念系统，我们如何在它们之间做出选择？更重要的是，一致性本身就预设了逻辑原则，特别是无矛盾律。任何认识论理论都必须假设某些东西为已知，这就涉及某种「循环」。关键问题不是如何避免所有循环，而是哪种世界观能够为必要的预设提供最好的解释。",
        "response_en": "Both foundationalism and coherentism face serious epistemological problems. Foundationalism claims there are self-evident basic beliefs, but what counts as 'self-evident'? How can we determine certain beliefs are genuinely self-evident rather than our biases? Descartes' 'I think, therefore I am' seems self-evident, but it presupposes the laws of logic (such as the law of identity) and the stability of linguistic meaning—which are themselves not self-evident. Modern epistemology has long abandoned the project of finding indubitable foundational beliefs. Coherentism's problem is that multiple mutually consistent yet contradictory belief systems may exist—how do we choose among them? More importantly, coherence itself presupposes logical principles, particularly the law of non-contradiction. Any epistemological theory must assume certain things as known, which involves some kind of 'circularity.' The key question is not how to avoid all circularity, but which worldview can provide the most consistent explanation for necessary presuppositions."
