        "objection_en": "Classical apologetics is better suited for dialogue with unbelievers because it starts from a common rational foundation",
        "response_zh": "这种观点虽然表面上合理，但基于一个有问题的假设：真正存在「共同的理性基础」。范泰尔正确地指出，堕落使人类理性被罪扭曲，非基督徒不可能在认识神的问题上保持中性。他们会系统性地抑制和扭曲关于神的真理(罗马书1:18-20)。假装存在中性的理性基础实际上是给非基督徒一种错误的安全感，使他们以为可以用堕落的理性来审判神的启示。然而，这不意味着我们应该避免与非基督徒理性对话。相反，我们应该在对话中既展示他们世界观的内在矛盾，又显明基督教世界观如何为理性本身提供基础。这种方法虽然初看起来更具挑战性，但实际上更有效，因为它触及问题的根源。",
        "response_en": "While this view seems reasonable on the surface, it is based on a problematic assumption: that a truly 'common rational foundation' exists. Van Til correctly pointed out that the Fall has corrupted human reason by sin, and non-Christians cannot remain neutral on the question of knowing God. They systematically suppress and distort the truth about God (Romans 1:18-20). Pretending a neutral rational foundation exists actually gives non-Christians a false sense of security, letting them think they can judge God's revelation using fallen reason. However, this does not mean we should avoid rational dialogue with non-Christians. On the contrary, we should demonstrate the internal contradictions of their worldview while also showing how the Christian worldview provides the very foundation for reason itself. Though this approach may seem more challenging at first glance, it is actually more effective because it addresses the root of the problem."
