        "response_en": "The 20th century conducted the largest 'experiment' on this hypothesis. The French Revolution's Reign of Terror, Soviet Gulags, the Nazi Holocaust, China's Cultural Revolution—these secular or anti-religious regimes caused more deaths than all prior religious conflicts combined. As Dostoevsky perceived: 'If there is no God, everything is permitted.' When transcendent moral frameworks are removed, the state or ideology fills the vacuum, often leading to more extreme violence. The problem isn't religion but the fallenness of the human heart—precisely Christianity's core diagnosis."
