    "id": "obj-004",
    "target_worldview": "general",
    "topic_zh": "地狱的公正性：慈爱的上帝怎能永刑？",
    "topic_en": "The Justice of Hell: How Can a Loving God Punish Eternally?",
    "core_argument_zh": "地狱的教义是基督教中最令人不安也最常被误解的教导之一。但在深入思考后，我们会发现它恰恰是上帝公义、圣洁和对人的尊重的体现。首先，我们必须理解罪的严重性不仅取决于行为本身，更取决于所冒犯的对象。冒犯同事和冒犯总统有不同后果，这不是因为行为不同，而是因为被冒犯者的地位不同。罪是对无限圣洁、无限尊荣的上帝的冒犯，因此其严重性也是无限的。乔纳森·爱德华兹在《落在愤怒之上帝手中的罪人》中论证：对无限存在者的冒犯配得无限的惩罚。\n\n改革宗神学家D.A.卡森在《上帝难解之事》（The Difficult Doctrine of the Love of God）中指出，现代人往往将上帝的爱简化为感性的温情，而忽视了圣经中上帝之爱的复杂性——包括圣约之爱、公义之爱和选民之爱。一个真正公义的法官不会对罪恶视而不见。如果上帝对希特勒的暴行和母亲特蕾莎的服侍给予完全相同的最终结局，那这个上帝恰恰是不公义的。\n\n更深层地说，C.S.路易斯在《痛苦的问题》和《大离婚》中提出了一个深刻的洞见：地狱从某种意义上说是人自己选择的结果。地狱不是上帝把人拖进去的酷刑室，而是人持续拒绝上帝的最终状态。路易斯写道：「地狱的门是从里面锁上的。」上帝尊重人的自由选择——如果一个人终其一生拒绝上帝、拒绝悔改，上帝不会强迫他进入天堂，因为对于一个恨上帝的人来说，永远与上帝同在才是真正的地狱。",
    "core_argument_en": "The doctrine of hell is one of Christianity's most disturbing and most misunderstood teachings. Yet upon deeper reflection, it proves to be an expression of God's justice, holiness, and respect for human agency. First, sin's severity depends not only on the act itself but on the one offended. Offending a colleague and offending a president carry different consequences—not because the act differs, but because of the offended party's status. Sin offends an infinitely holy, infinitely glorious God, so its severity is infinite. Jonathan Edwards argued in 'Sinners in the Hands of an Angry God' that offense against an infinite being merits infinite punishment.\n\nReformed theologian D.A. Carson notes in The Difficult Doctrine of the Love of God that moderns often reduce God's love to sentimental warmth, ignoring Scripture's complex portrait—covenant love, justice-love, and electing love. A truly just judge cannot overlook evil. If God gave Hitler's atrocities and Mother Teresa's service the exact same final outcome, that God would be unjust.\n\nMore profoundly, C.S. Lewis offers a deep insight in The Problem of Pain and The Great Divorce: hell is, in a sense, the result of human choice. Hell isn't a torture chamber God drags people into, but the final state of those who persistently reject God. Lewis wrote: 'The doors of hell are locked on the inside.' God respects human free choice—if someone spends their entire life rejecting God and refusing repentance, God will not force them into heaven, because for someone who hates God, being eternally with God would be the real hell.",
    "common_objections": [
      {
        "objection_zh": "有限的罪怎么配得无限的惩罚？这根本不成比例。",
        "objection_en": "How can finite sins deserve infinite punishment? That's completely disproportionate.",
        "response_zh": "这一反驳假设罪的严重性只由行为的持续时间决定，但实际上罪的严重性主要由被冒犯者的尊严决定。打一个陌生人和打总统后果截然不同。更重要的是，地狱中的人并非因有限的罪受无限的罚——他们在地狱中继续犯罪、继续悖逆上帝，因此刑罚也持续。正如提摩太·凯勒所说：地狱中的人并不悔改——他们对上帝的恨和对自我的崇拜只会加深，因此他们持续招致公义的审判。此外，基督在十字架上为信徒承担了这一无限的刑罚——无限的上帝承受了无限的刑罚，这是福音恩典的核心。",
        "response_en": "This objection assumes sin's severity is determined only by the act's duration, but severity primarily depends on the dignity of the one offended. Striking a stranger and striking the president carry vastly different consequences. More importantly, those in hell aren't receiving infinite punishment for finite sins—they continue sinning and rebelling against God in hell, so punishment continues. As Timothy Keller says: people in hell don't repent—their hatred of God and self-worship only deepen, so they continue incurring just judgment. Moreover, Christ bore this infinite punishment on the cross for believers—the infinite God absorbed infinite punishment, which is the Gospel's core."
      },
      {
        "objection_zh": "一个慈爱的父亲不会把孩子送进永刑。",
        "objection_en": "A loving father wouldn't send his children to eternal punishment.",
        "response_zh": "但一个好父亲也不会对孩子的恶行毫无回应。如果你的孩子杀了人，一个真正爱正义的父亲会为正义得到伸张而感恩，即使这意味着孩子要面对后果。上帝的爱不是纵容的溺爱，而是圣洁的爱。而且，上帝已经做了一切来拯救人脱离地狱——祂差遣自己的独生子死在十字架上。约翰福音3:16-17清楚地说：「上帝差祂的儿子降世，不是要定世人的罪，乃是要叫世人因祂得救。」上帝不愿任何人灭亡（彼得后书3:9），但祂不会强迫任何人接受救恩。",
        "response_en": "But a good father also wouldn't ignore his child's evil. If your child committed murder, a father who truly loves justice would be grateful for justice being served, even if it means consequences. God's love isn't permissive indulgence but holy love. Moreover, God has done everything possible to save people from hell—He sent His only Son to die on the cross. John 3:16-17 clearly states God sent His Son not to condemn the world but to save it. God doesn't wish anyone to perish (2 Peter 3:9), but He won't force anyone to accept salvation."
      },
      {
        "objection_zh": "为什么不能让灵魂消灭（annihilationism），而非永远受苦？",
        "objection_en": "Why not annihilation instead of eternal suffering?",
        "response_zh": "灵魂消灭论（annihilationism）在教会历史中确实有少数支持者，如约翰·斯托特（John Stott）晚年也曾倾向这一立场。但传统改革宗和天主教立场认为，圣经的证据更支持永刑的教导：耶稣在马太福音25:46使用了相同的希腊词「永远」（aiōnios）来同时描述永生和永刑；启示录14:11和20:10都描述了无止境的刑罚。更重要的是，人是按上帝的形像被造的，灵魂具有不可消灭的尊严——即使在悖逆中，人仍是上帝的形像承载者，这使得灵魂消灭在神学上成为问题。",
        "response_en": "Annihilationism has had some supporters in church history—even John Stott leaned toward it later in life. But traditional Reformed and Catholic positions hold that biblical evidence better supports eternal punishment: Jesus uses the same Greek word 'eternal' (aiōnios) in Matthew 25:46 for both eternal life and eternal punishment; Revelation 14:11 and 20:10 describe unending punishment. More importantly, humans are made in God's image with indestructible dignity—even in rebellion, humans remain God's image-bearers, making annihilation theologically problematic."
      }
    ],
