        "objection_en": "All roads lead to Rome—don't all religions essentially teach people to be good?",
        "response_zh": "这种说法虽然善意，但在事实上站不住脚。世界主要宗教在最核心的问题上存在根本性矛盾：上帝是一位（基督教、伊斯兰教）还是无数（印度教）还是不存在（上座部佛教）？人死后是复活（基督教）、轮回（印度教/佛教）还是进入天堂或地狱（伊斯兰教）？救赎是靠恩典（基督教）还是靠行为（伊斯兰教）还是靠觉悟（佛教）？这些不是细枝末节的差异，而是关于实在本质的根本矛盾。逻辑不矛盾律告诉我们：矛盾的命题不可能同时为真。说「所有宗教本质相同」恰恰暴露了对各宗教的浅薄了解。",
        "response_en": "This well-intentioned claim doesn't hold up factually. Major world religions fundamentally contradict each other on the most core questions: Is God one (Christianity, Islam), many (Hinduism), or nonexistent (Theravada Buddhism)? After death—resurrection (Christianity), reincarnation (Hinduism/Buddhism), or paradise/hell (Islam)? Salvation by grace (Christianity), works (Islam), or enlightenment (Buddhism)? These aren't minor differences but fundamental contradictions about the nature of reality. The law of non-contradiction tells us contradictory propositions cannot both be true. Saying 'all religions are essentially the same' reveals shallow understanding of each religion."
