        "response_en": "Most Reformed scholars do affirm Adam and Eve as historical figures—this is crucial for the doctrine of original sin. Paul draws a parallel between Adam and Christ in Romans 5:12-21: 'Through the disobedience of the one man the many were made sinners, so also through the obedience of the one man the many will be made righteous.' If Adam isn't historically real, Paul's argument loses its foundation. The key point: we can believe Adam was historical while remaining open about the specific mechanism of God's creation of Adam. C. John Collins argues in Did Adam and Eve Really Exist? that Adam could be God's specially created first human pair, or a representative God chose from an existing human population and endowed with unique status. Either way, core doctrines are preserved."
