    "core_argument_zh": "「圣经充满矛盾」是对基督教信仰最常见的攻击之一。然而，对所谓矛盾的仔细分析表明，绝大多数可以通过正确的解经方法得到合理解释。理解古代文学的写作惯例和圣经的文体多样性是关键。\n\n首先，需要明确什么是「矛盾」。逻辑学上的矛盾是指在同一时间、同一方面对同一事物做出相反的断言。仅仅因为两段经文使用了不同的措辞、从不同角度描述同一事件、或记载了不同的细节，并不构成逻辑矛盾。格雷格·科克尔（Greg Koukl）在其护教方法论中反复强调：差异（difference）不等于矛盾（contradiction）。四个证人对同一事件的不同描述恰恰证明了他们的独立性和可信度。\n\n以常见的「矛盾」为例：四福音对复活清晨来到坟墓的妇女人数描述不同。马太提到两个马利亚，马可提到三个人，路加提到更多人。但这并非矛盾——提到两个人并不否认还有其他人在场。这与我们日常叙述事件的方式完全一致：不同叙述者会选择性地提及不同的参与者。克雷格·布隆伯格（Craig Blomberg）在《耶稣与福音书的历史可靠性》中系统性地处理了福音书之间的差异，表明这些差异在古代史学标准下完全可以理解。\n\n学者格利森·阿彻（Gleason Archer）在《圣经难题百科全书》中逐一分析了500多处所谓的圣经矛盾，为每一处提供了基于语言学、历史背景和文体分析的合理解释。这并不意味着每一个难题都有简单的答案，但它确实表明「圣经充满矛盾」是一种不经深入研究就下的结论。",
    "core_argument_en": "'The Bible is full of contradictions' is one of the most common attacks on Christianity. However, careful analysis reveals that the vast majority can be reasonably explained through proper hermeneutical methods. Understanding ancient literary conventions and biblical genre diversity is key.\n\nFirst, we must define 'contradiction.' A logical contradiction asserts opposite things about the same subject at the same time in the same sense. Different wording, different perspectives on the same event, or different recorded details do not constitute logical contradictions. Greg Koukl repeatedly emphasizes: difference is not contradiction. Four witnesses giving different descriptions of the same event actually demonstrates their independence and credibility.\n\nConsider a common 'contradiction': the four Gospels differ on how many women visited the tomb Easter morning. Matthew mentions two Marys, Mark names three, Luke mentions more. This isn't contradictory—mentioning two people doesn't deny others were present. This matches how we naturally recount events: different narrators selectively mention different participants. Craig Blomberg in The Historical Reliability of the Gospels systematically addresses Gospel differences, showing they're fully understandable by ancient historiographical standards.\n\nScholar Gleason Archer in Encyclopedia of Bible Difficulties analyzes 500+ alleged contradictions, providing linguistically, historically, and genre-informed explanations for each. This doesn't mean every difficulty has a simple answer, but it demonstrates that 'the Bible is full of contradictions' is a conclusion drawn without serious investigation.",
    "common_objections": [
      {
        "objection_zh": "犹大是怎么死的？马太说上吊，使徒行传说身子仆倒肠子流出来——这不是明显的矛盾吗？",
        "objection_en": "How did Judas die? Matthew says hanging, Acts says falling and bursting open—isn't that an obvious contradiction?",
        "response_zh": "这两段经文很可能描述的是同一事件的不同阶段。犹大上吊后（马太福音27:5），绳子或树枝断裂，尸体坠落到下方的岩石上，导致身体破裂（使徒行传1:18）。在古代叙事中，不同作者记录同一事件的不同方面是常见做法。关键是两位作者都同意犹大死于非命——这是核心事实。细节的互补性而非矛盾性，恰恰增加了记载的可信度。格利森·阿彻在《圣经难题百科全书》中对此有详细分析。",
        "response_en": "These passages likely describe different stages of the same event. After Judas hanged himself (Matthew 27:5), the rope or branch broke, and the body fell onto rocks below, causing it to burst open (Acts 1:18). In ancient narrative, different authors recording different aspects of the same event was standard practice. Crucially, both authors agree Judas died violently—that's the core fact. The complementary rather than contradictory details actually increase credibility. Gleason Archer provides detailed analysis in Encyclopedia of Bible Difficulties."
      },
