    "core_argument_zh": "灵恩运动对教会复兴有重要贡献，但某些极端分支已经严重偏离了圣经正统。需要辨别的极端现象包括：（1）「成功神学」（又称健康财富福音），宣称信心足够就必然带来健康和财富；（2）「使徒先知运动」（NAR），声称当代存在与初代使徒同等权柄的使徒和先知，可以接受新的启示；（3）各种不受控制的「圣灵彰显」，如「圣笑」、模仿动物叫声、「被圣灵击倒」等。约翰·麦克阿瑟（John MacArthur）在《奇异之火》中尖锐批评这些现象缺乏圣经根据。迈克尔·乐文（Michael Brown）虽然从灵恩派内部立场出发，也在《Playing with Holy Fire》中承认运动中存在严重偏差需要纠正。从圣经看，成功神学直接矛盾于耶稣关于十字架和苦难的教导（太16:24；腓1:29）——保罗和众使徒的一生就是最好的反证。关于新使徒，以弗所书2:20将使徒和先知定位为教会的「根基」而非持续的职分，犹大书3节提到的信仰「一次交付圣徒」表明启示的完整性。关于极端现象，哥林多前书14:33「上帝不是叫人混乱的」和14:40「凡事都要规规矩矩按着次序行」设定了清晰的标准。山姆·史东（Sam Storms）提醒我们，辨别不是熄灭圣灵（帖前5:19），而是「凡事察验」（帖前5:21）——在开放与谨慎之间保持圣经的平衡。",
    "core_argument_en": "The charismatic movement has made important contributions to church renewal, but certain extreme branches have seriously departed from biblical orthodoxy. Extremes requiring discernment include: (1) 'Prosperity theology' (health-and-wealth gospel) claiming sufficient faith guarantees health and wealth; (2) the New Apostolic Reformation (NAR) claiming contemporary apostles with authority equal to the original apostles who can receive new revelation; (3) uncontrolled 'Spirit manifestations' like 'holy laughter,' animal sounds, and 'slaying in the Spirit.' John MacArthur in 'Strange Fire' sharply critiques these phenomena as lacking biblical support. Michael Brown, writing from within the charismatic tradition in 'Playing with Holy Fire,' also acknowledges serious deviations requiring correction. Biblically, prosperity theology directly contradicts Jesus' teachings on the cross and suffering (Matt 16:24; Phil 1:29) — Paul and the apostles' lives are the best counter-evidence. On new apostles, Ephesians 2:20 positions apostles and prophets as the church's 'foundation,' not an ongoing office; Jude 3's faith 'once for all delivered to the saints' indicates revelation's completeness. On extreme phenomena, 1 Corinthians 14:33 ('God is not a God of confusion') and 14:40 ('all things should be done decently and in order') set clear standards. Sam Storms reminds us that discernment is not quenching the Spirit (1 Thess 5:19) but 'testing everything' (1 Thess 5:21) — maintaining biblical balance between openness and caution.",
