        "response_en": "Indeed, certain Hindu schools (especially Advaita Vedanta) can be understood as a form of 'monism,' but this differs essentially from Christian monotheism. Advaita's 'One' is attributeless, impersonal pure consciousness; Christianity's God is personal, volitional, freely capable of love and creation. Moreover, there is no internal Hindu consensus on this: the Vedas contain extensive polytheistic texts, and popular Hindu practice centers on worship of multiple deities. Reducing Hinduism to 'monotheism' oversimplifies its rich diversity. The key question is not 'how many gods' but whether ultimate reality is personal or impersonal."
